The replace_all_re regex did not allow string identifiers with dashes, amongst other allowed special characters.

Relevant bit of http://ftp.math.utah.edu/pub/tex/bibtex/bibtex.web (couldn't find the parser in a more recent TeX distro...):

for i:=0 to @'177 do id_class[i] := legal_id_char;
for i:=0 to @'37 do id_class[i] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[space] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[tab] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[double_quote] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[number_sign] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[comment] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[single_quote] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[left_paren] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[right_paren] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[comma] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[equals_sign] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[left_brace] := illegal_id_char;
id_class[right_brace] := illegal_id_char;

This was throwing an `NgxParserDirectiveContextError`:
```nginx
http {
    upstream {
        state /path/to/state/file.conf;
    }
}
```

Although it shouldn't've, as you can see here:  
http://nginx.org/en/docs/http/ngx_http_upstream_module.html#state  
http://nginx.org/en/docs/stream/ngx_stream_upstream_module.html#state

@fmarier, I've updated the Debian packaging over the last few days, based off of the git history as of dd4b8e87cbddff68273104825aabef0b34f9b284.

I broke it out into multiple binary packages, verified all the tests run clean, and tested the installation.  Everything seems to work.  Lintian is complaining mostly about expected things - UNRELEASED, as well as a couple of manpage errors - but nothing that's too unexpected.  I spent a couple of days trying to use the standard toolset to get this to build properly - pybuild, etc., but ended up having to go with a more manual process.  I squashed a lot of my attempts down in this branch, but an alternate strategy is still extant on my branch at hlieberman/debian-failed-attempt.

Please let me know if this looks good to you, and upstream can merge after your thumbs up.

